<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING BRIEFING: GOLF BUFFS SHOW UP IN ODDEST PLACES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Amy Alcott is stuck on 29 victories, one shy of the number needed to qualify 
for the LPGA Hall of Fame. She got a rude reminder during a tournament in 
Nashville, Tenn.  
</P>
<P>
 "I opened the door in my hotel and I was trying to get my newspaper," Alcott 
recalled in Golf Digest. "I didn't have any clothes on and I figured it was 
safe because it was 5:45 in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm standing there naked and there is this guy standing there going, 'I hope 
you win your 30th soon.' 
</P>
<P>
 "I looked at the guy and said, 'Thanks. How did you know it was me?' 
</P>
<P>
 "He said, 'Oh, I'd recognize you anywhere.' " 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia time: Who holds the NFL record for most pass receptions in a season? 
</P>
<P>
 Up to date: Bernie Lincicome of the Chicago Tribune writing on the Chicago 
Cubs: 
</P>
<P>
 "This is a team that once tried a college of coaches, that resisted the 
electric light bulb (night games) until it was sure it was not just a fad, that 
treats failure like an annuity." 
</P>
<P>
 Sideshow: Eccentric Dennis Rodman of the San Antonio Spurs regards himself as 
a showman. "I keep things on edge. People come to see me so they can see 
something different," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 No doubt about it. These days Rodman has fuschia-colored hair and body 
piercings, including one in his navel and one in his nose. 
</P>
<P>
 Thud!Ronnie Lott, the veteran New Jork Jet defensive back, describes in a book 
"Total Impact" his approach to the game: 
</P>
<P>
 "Grab a football, throw it in the air, and before you can catch it, have your 
best friend belt you with a baseball bat. No shoulder pads. No helmet. Just 
you, your best friend and the biggest Louisville Slugger you can find. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's what it feels like to be hit by me." 
</P>
<P>
 Bear hunting: USC's 61-0 blowout of California on Saturday wasn't the largest 
margin of victory over the Golden Bears in the series. 
</P>
<P>
 Howard Jones' Thundering Herd team routed Cal, 74-0, at the Coliseum in 1930. 
</P>
<P>
 Come again?Steve Obradovich, a former USC football player, recalled the time 
that his friend George Brett gave him some old bats. 
</P>
<P>
 When Obradovich asked for more, Brett replied: "These things don't grow on 
trees." 
</P>
<P>
 Fish story: Tom Krasovic writing in the San Diego Union-Tribune on San Diego 
State's 52-35 loss to Wyoming on Saturday:  
</P>
<P>
 "LARAMIE, Wyo. -- Here in the state of cutthroat trout, San Diego State turned 
in a flounder of a football outing yesterday." 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia answer: Sterling Sharpe of the Green Bay Packers, with 112 in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 Quotebook: Terry Francona, manager of the double-A Birmingham Barons: "You 
could enter Michael Jordan in a Ping-Pong tournament and people would come. 
He's a magnet." MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102494-0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 091627 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
October 24, 1994, Monday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 3; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
684 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLAN MALAMUD: NOTES ON A SCORECARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN MALAMUD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 How wacky was the Saints' 37-34 victory over the Rams on Sunday in New 
Orleans?. . . Jim Everett wasn't mentioned until the 15th paragraph of the 
Associated Press' game story. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Everett's spot of revenge was lost in the commotion over kickoff returns for 
touchdowns of 92 and 98 yards by teammate Tyrone Hughes, a 98-yard run with a 
fumble by the Rams' Toby Wright, and something really bizarre, a 103-yard punt 
return by the Rams' Robert Bailey. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 The day after USC's Cole Ford put nine consecutive kickoffs into the 
California end zone and had none returned, Hughes was able to take advantage of 
the new NFL rules that work against the kicker. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 NFL Films will have a treasure in the clip that shows Bailey coming out of the 
end zone and running the length of the field untouched while the Saints, who 
thought the punt had been whistled dead for a touchback, strolled to their 
bench. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps Everett, who had a pretty nice day staying on his feet and throwing 
the ball, will get a little more attention when the Saints play the Raiders 
Nov. 20 at the Coliseum and the Rams Dec. 4 at Anaheim Stadium. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 In recording their first Coliseum victory of the season, the Raiders were 
unusually efficient against Atlanta. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 They didn't commit a turnover after their first scrimmage play and were 
penalized only 31 yards, compared to 70 for the Falcons. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 About all the coach, Art Shell, and the quarterback, Jeff Hostetler, appeared 
to exchange on the sidelines were handshakes. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 The play calling was the Raiders' best this season and their new starter at 
tailback, Hundred-Yard Harvey Williams, had his workload increased. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 If you are a believer in the law of averages, the Denver Broncos' narrow 
victory over the San Diego Chargers didn't come as a surprise. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 John Robinson tried to downplay USC's victory over Washington on opening day. 
. . . 
</P>
<P>
 "We're not a good team right now," the coach said Sept. 3. "I think we will be 
in November." . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The Trojans appear to be a trifle ahead of schedule, having devoured 
California, 61-0, on the third Saturday of October at the Coliseum. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Their next game is in November -- on the 5th at Pullman against Washington 
State after taking a week off. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The most remarkable statistic of a young team that is becoming more efficient 
every week is that it hasn't committed a turnover in the last 15 quarters. . . 
.  
</P>
<P>
 Now for the quarterback situation. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 If it's a controversy, it's the kind that most coaches would like to have. . . 
.  
</P>
<P>
 Rob Johnson probably will start against Washington State -- remember, his 
injured ankle will have an extra week to heal -- but Robinson won't hesitate to 
summon Brad Otton again if necessary. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Otton, the sophomore transfer from Weber State, has shown uncommon poise and a 
strong, accurate throwing arm the past three games. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Pacific 10 Conference race that appeared to be narrowing down to Arizona 
and Washington State now includes USC and Oregon. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The Trojans and Ducks must be encouraged by the way UCLA's Wayne Cook was able 
to pass against the Desert Swarm defense in Tucson. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 In fact, the Bruins would have been competitive down to the wire if their 
secondary hadn't broken down on some key third-down situations. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Getting his kicks was UCLA punter Darren Schager, who averaged 48 yards on 
seven punts and kept pinning the Wildcats deep in their territory. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Pac-10 Game of the Week: Arizona at Oregon. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Wisconsin, which lost to Minnesota, has gone from one of the most surprising 
teams in the nation to one of the most disappointing. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Don't expect Scott Bentley, the Florida State kicker who appeared on the cover 
of Sports Illustrated before he ever played in a college game, to make any 
magazine cover again. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Colorado running back Rashaan Salaam has moved to the head of the class of 
Heisman Trophy candidates, at least for the moment. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Funny, but Ohio State Coach John Cooper, who poured it on against Purdue, 
never seems to get the opportunity against Michigan. 
</P>
