<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA VOICES / A FORUM FOR COMMUNITY ISSUES: ON LOCATION; 'IS 
THIS THE END OF BRITAIN'S ROYAL FAMILY?' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Princess Diana's supposed lover has bared all about intimate moments while 
Diana was still with Charles. Prince Charles has bared all for a book that says 
he had a terribly unhappy childhood and was forced to marry Diana. The 
continuing scandals have commentators predicting the end of the British 
monarchy, but love of the royals runs deep among Britons, even (or maybe 
especially) the 1 million or so who live far from home in Southern California. 
JAMES BLAIR went to the Kings Head Bar in Santa Monica to check the pulse of 
local Britons. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 LLOYD G. SCOTT 
</P>
<P>
 Construction worker, from London, three years in Southern California 
</P>
<P>
 I understand that Prince Charles said he was forced to marry Diana even though 
he didn't love her. Well, the Royal Family's been doing that for hundreds of 
years. Originally, the children used to marry princesses or princes from 
Germany or France just to keep the peace among nations. So it's nothing new. 
The fact is that now, through the media, it comes out. But I think the Royal 
Family is the best thing for England. I can't understand why anybody would like 
to say that they should be disbanded. 
</P>
<P>
 Absolutely, there's a future for the Royal Family. They do a good job. Even if 
Charles doesn't become the king, one of his sons will. MONICA MORRIS 
</P>
<P>
 Sociologist, from London, 26 years in Southern California 
</P>
<P>
 I was never a royalist and always wondered what the Royal Family was for. I 
was told that they played a very, very important function. Having a strong 
Royal Family at the helm was thought to be invaluable in holding the society, 
the state, together. I really marvel at the way that illusions have been so 
easily created and firmly believed in. The illusion of this incredible love 
affair -- films were made about Charles and his Diana, this lovely fairy story 
-- was created presumably quite deliberately and just as easily destroyed. The 
Royal Family's been under fire for quite a long time, what with Princess 
Margaret and her carryings-on, the whole crowd in fact. The poor Queen is in 
terrible disarray. MELANIE ETTIENE 
</P>
<P>
 Bartender, from Epsom, Surrey, five years in Southern California 
</P>
<P>
 It's all become quite tarnished. They were supposed to stay married. They 
weren't supposed to cheat. Well, they weren't supposed to get caught. I 
wouldn't be upset now if the monarchy were to vanish. Not now, no. 
</P>
<P>
 But it's always been quite a draw for tourism and it's something that 
Americans have always been very big on. I always talk with people from our 
King's Head gift shop next door. They always come in and ask us about what's 
going on. It's definitely a big tourist draw so I think that would really hurt 
if that were to happen; but I don't think that is what will happen. I think 
they'll probably try to straighten out Prince Edward, clean him up. I think 
he'll probably become king. 
</P>
<P>
 I don't think Queen Elizabeth will abdicate. If Charles and Diana had stayed 
together I think, yes, she probably would have. I think she'll stay on to the 
bitter end, or at least until she feels secure that there is somebody to take 
over. GLEN BISHOP 
</P>
<P>
 Plastering contractor, from Chelmsford, Essex, 10 years in Southern California 
</P>
<P>
 Personally, I feel that the Royal Family is only human like the rest of us. 
They're going to go through everything that normal people go through. People 
tend to forget that the soul of the English people is our Royal Family. They 
bring so much good and investment into the country that I honestly feel they'll 
be along for a lot longer. 
</P>
<P>
 The media blow things all up and everybody will be talking. When it comes down 
to it, everything will be the same as it was before because so many people love 
the Royal Family in England. You can't blame the economy on the Royal Family. 
That's something to do with the government and the fact that we've got a world 
economy now, not just a British economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
